  "prompt": "Complete an orbital diagram for scandium (Sc).?",
  "response": "To create an orbital diagram for **Scandium (Sc)**, which has an atomic number of **21**, you'll need to distribute its **21 electrons** across the various atomic orbitals following the principles of electron configuration:\n\n1. **Aufbau Principle**: Electrons fill orbitals starting with the lowest energy levels first.\n2. **Pauli Exclusion Principle**: Each orbital can hold a maximum of two electrons with opposite spins.\n3. **Hund's Rule**: Electrons will singly occupy degenerate orbitals (orbitals of the same energy) before pairing up.\n\n### Scandium (Sc) Electron Configuration:\nThe electron configuration for Scandium is:\n```\n1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b2 3p\u2076 4s\u00b2 3d\u00b9\n```\n\n### Orbital Diagram:\nBelow is the orbital diagram for Scandium, showing the distribution of electrons in each orbital. Each box represents an orbital, and the arrows (\u2191 or \u2193) represent electrons with their spins.\n\n```\n1s  : \u2191\u2193\n2s  : \u2191\u2193\n2p  : \u2191\u2193   \u2191\u2193   \u2191\u2193\n3s  : \u2191\u2193\n3p  : \u2191\u2193   \u2191\u2193   \u2191\u2193\n4s  : \u2191\u2193\n3d  : \u2191    \u25a1    \u25a1    \u25a1    \u25a1\n```\n\n**Explanation:**\n\n- **1s, 2s, 3s, and 4s Orbitals**: Each of these orbitals is fully occupied with two electrons (\u2191\u2193), indicating paired electrons.\n  \n- **2p and 3p Orbitals**: These have three orbitals each, and all are fully occupied with two electrons per orbital (\u2191\u2193).\n\n- **3d Orbital**: Scandium has one electron in the 3d subshell. This is represented by a single upward arrow (\u2191) in one of the five d orbitals, with the remaining four d orbitals (\u25a1) empty.\n\n### Visual Representation:\n\n```\n1s  : [\u2191\u2193]\n\n2s  : [\u2191\u2193]\n\n2p  : [\u2191\u2193] [\u2191\u2193] [\u2191\u2193]\n\n3s  : [\u2191\u2193]\n\n3p  : [\u2191\u2193] [\u2191\u2193] [\u2191\u2193]\n\n4s  : [\u2191\u2193]\n\n3d  : [\u2191 ] [ ] [ ] [ ] [ ]\n```\n\nEach pair of brackets `[ ]` represents an orbital, and the arrows inside denote the electrons' spins. This diagram accurately reflects Scandium's electron distribution according to the principles of quantum chemistry.",
